data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **Cosmos DB provider removes the sync-over-async opt-in entirely**. The escape hatch you configured in .NET 10 (suppressing `CosmosEventId.SyncNotSupported`) no longer exists.

Every synchronous LINQ operator and `SaveChanges()` call against the Cosmos provider now throws `InvalidOperationException` unconditionally — **no workaround**.

### Affected methods in your code

| Sync (breaks) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `.ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(...)` | `.FirstAsync(...)` |
| `.Count()` | `.CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `.SaveChangesAsync()` |

### Fixed repository

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `Add()` stays synchronous — it's an in-memory tracking call, not I/O.
- All callers up the stack must also go `async`/`await` (controllers, services, etc.).
- Remove the `CosmosEventId.SyncNotSupported` warning suppression from your `DbContext` configuration — it will cause a build error since the event ID no longer exists.
